  "prompt": "What are the causes of having itchy small blisters on my fingers?",
  "response": "Itchy small blisters on your fingers can be caused by a variety of conditions. Some common causes include:\n\n1. **Allergic Reactions**: Contact dermatitis can occur from exposure to irritants or allergens, such as soaps, detergents, or certain metals.\n\n2. **Eczema (Atopic Dermatitis)**: A chronic skin condition that can cause itchy, blister-like lesions, usually associated with dry skin.\n\n3. **Dyshidrotic Eczema**: This specific type of eczema leads to small, itchy blisters on the hands and fingers, often triggered by stress, humidity, or allergens.\n\n4. **Fungal Infections**: Conditions like tinea manuum (a fungal infection of the hand) can cause blistering and itching.\n\n5. **Viral Infections**: Certain viral infections can cause blisters on the skin. For instance, herpes simplex can lead to blisters in localized areas.\n\n6. **Scabies**: An infestation by mites can cause intense itching and small blisters or bumps.\n\n7. **Impetigo**: A bacterial skin infection that can lead to blistering lesions, often more common in children.\n\n8. **Insect Bites**: Certain insect bites can cause localized blistering and itching.\n\n9. **Heat Rash**: Blocked sweat glands can lead to small blisters in hot and humid conditions.\n\n10. **Pemphigus or other autoimmune disorders**: These conditions can lead to the formation of blisters on various body areas.\n\nIf you're experiencing persistent or worsening symptoms, it's important to consult with a healthcare professional for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.",
